3. S3 as Artifactory storage backend	Store all binaries in S3 instead of local disk

Here are the steps to set up Artifactory with S3 as its storage backend on a personal laptop. Since you're working locally, I'll use MinIO as an S3-compatible backend (no AWS account needed), with Artifactory OSS running via Docker.

Prerequisites
Docker & Docker Compose installed
~4 GB RAM free
Ports 8081, 8082, 9000, 9001 available

Step 1 — Create a project directory
mkdir ~/artifactory-s3-lab && cd ~/artifactory-s3-lab

Step 2 — Create docker-compose.yml
version: "3.8"

services:
  minio:
    image: minio/minio:latest
    container_name: minio
    ports:
      - "9000:9000"   # S3 API
      - "9001:9001"   # Web console
    environment:
      MINIO_ROOT_USER: minioadmin
      MINIO_ROOT_PASSWORD: minioadmin
    volumes:
      - minio_data:/data
    command: server /data --console-address ":9001"
    healthcheck:
      test: ["CMD", "curl", "-f", "http://localhost:9000/minio/health/live"]
      interval: 10s
      timeout: 5s
      retries: 5

  artifactory:
    image: releases-docker.jfrog.io/jfrog/artifactory-oss:latest
    container_name: artifactory
    ports:
      - "8081:8081"
      - "8082:8082"
    volumes:
      - artifactory_data:/var/opt/jfrog/artifactory
    depends_on:
      minio:
        condition: service_healthy
    environment:
      - JF_SHARED_DATABASE_TYPE=derby   # embedded DB for local use

volumes:
  minio_data:
  artifactory_data:

Step 3 — Start the stack
docker compose up -d

Wait ~60 seconds for Artifactory to initialize.

Step 4 — Create the S3 bucket in MinIO
# Install MinIO client
docker run --rm --network host \
  minio/mc alias set local http://localhost:9000 minioadmin minioadmin

docker run --rm --network host \
  minio/mc mb local/artifactory-binaries

Or open the MinIO console at http://localhost:9001 (user: minioadmin, pass: minioadmin) and create a bucket named artifactory-binaries.

Step 5 — Configure Artifactory to use S3 storage
Create the storage config file that Artifactory reads:
mkdir -p ~/artifactory-s3-lab/artifactory-config

Create ~/artifactory-s3-lab/artifactory-config/binarystore.xml:

<config version="2">
    <chain template="s3-storage-v3"/>
    <provider id="s3-storage-v3" type="s3-storage-v3">
        <endpoint>http://minio:9000</endpoint>
        <bucketName>artifactory-binaries</bucketName>
        <region>us-east-1</region>
        <identity>minioadmin</identity>
        <credential>minioadmin</credential>
        <pathStyleAccess>true</pathStyleAccess>
        <testConnection>true</testConnection>
    </provider>
</config>

Copy it into the running container:
docker cp ~/artifactory-s3-lab/artifactory-config/binarystore.xml \
  artifactory:/var/opt/jfrog/artifactory/etc/artifactory/binarystore.xml

Step 6 — Restart Artifactory to apply the storage config

docker compose restart artifactory

Step 7 — Verify it works
Open Artifactory at http://localhost:8082 (default: admin / password)
Complete the setup wizard
Upload a binary to any repository
Check MinIO console at http://localhost:9001 → bucket artifactory-binaries — you should see the file stored there

Optional — Use real AWS S3
Replace the binarystore.xml provider block with:
<provider id="s3-storage-v3" type="s3-storage-v3">
    <bucketName>your-bucket-name</bucketName>
    <region>us-east-1</region>
    <identity>YOUR_AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID</identity>
    <credential>YOUR_AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY</credential>
    <pathStyleAccess>false</pathStyleAccess>
</provider>

Remove the <endpoint> line — Artifactory will use the default AWS S3 endpoint.

Teardown
cd ~/artifactory-s3-lab
docker compose down -v   # -v removes volumes too
